<dl id="n05097h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05097h">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05097h"> 97(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Spachhistorikers freud / is sprachbrauchers leid / (Schuchardt)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">But, however interesting such things may be to the historical linguist, there is no denying that to the users of French the modern simpler flexion is a gain as compared with this more complex system. <mark>&ldquo;Des sprachhistorikers freud ist des sprachbrauchers leid,&rdquo; as Schuchardt somewhere shrewdly remarks</mark>. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJLN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJLN"><cite title="source">Language: its Nature, Development and Origin</cite></a> (Jan 1922) 340</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
